# UDS Figma Plugin API Gotchas

These are Plugin API truths that bit the `generate-uds-figma-component`
factory build and would bite any other `use_figma` workflow the same way.
They are not UDS-specific — they apply to every script the agent writes
against the Figma Plugin API — but they were learned during UDS work,
so this rule lives alongside the rest of the UDS toolchain. If they
later get upstreamed into the active `figma-use` plugin skill's
`references/gotchas.md`, this rule can drop them and become a pointer.

## 1. Component identity is file-scope-dependent

Components in the **same file** as the script (visible in
`figma.root.children`) are LOCAL. Components in a **subscribed remote
library** are REMOTE. Same word "component" in both cases, different
resolution APIs. The two paths are not interchangeable.

### Resolution

| Where the component lives | API to get a reference | What `search_design_system` returns is useful for |
|---|---|---|
| Same file (LOCAL) | `await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('1234:567')` then pick `componentSet.children[0]` (or a specific variant by name) for `createInstance()` | Discovery of the node ID + the published KEY (which you won't use directly here) |
| Subscribed remote library (REMOTE) | `await figma.importComponentByKeyAsync(componentKey)` | The component KEY to pass to `importComponentByKeyAsync` |

`importComponentByKeyAsync` does NOT work on local components. The error
text is `Component with key "<...>" not found` which reads like the key
is wrong — actually the key is correct, the API is just the wrong one.

### Wrong → correct

```js
// WRONG — udc-icon-wrapper lives in the SAME file (UDS Components)
const iconWrapper = await figma.importComponentByKeyAsync('4ae9e6638c59062ad14115ff9631f20e86cca6fc');
//                                                           ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
//                                                           Throws: Component with key "..." not found

// CORRECT — same-file components resolve by node ID
const iconWrapperSet = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('5745:4541');
const iconWrapperDefault = iconWrapperSet.children[0];  // pick the default variant
const instance = iconWrapperDefault.createInstance();
```

## 2. `INSTANCE_SWAP` default value format depends on the same scope

`addComponentProperty(name, 'INSTANCE_SWAP', defaultValue)` accepts
**different formats** depending on whether the swap target is local
or remote:

| Target | `defaultValue` format | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Local component (same file) | Node ID with colon | `'5657:6767'` |
| Remote component (subscribed library) | Published component KEY | `'09f261dde3263fe70fe90028adf0b8f93ac19959'` |

The error when you pass the wrong format is:

```
in addComponentProperty: Property value is incompatible with component property type
```

This error reads like the property type is wrong (it isn't) — actually
the `defaultValue` format is just mis-scoped. Switch the format to
match the target's file scope.

### Wrong → correct (local target)

```js
// WRONG — local component, but passing the published KEY
const iconKey = '09f261dde3263fe70fe90028adf0b8f93ac19959';
fieldSet.addComponentProperty('leadingIcon', 'INSTANCE_SWAP', iconKey);
// Throws: Property value is incompatible with component property type

// CORRECT — local component, pass the node ID with colon
const iconNodeId = '5657:6767';
fieldSet.addComponentProperty('leadingIcon', 'INSTANCE_SWAP', iconNodeId);
```

### How to recover the right value

```js
// For local target: read the existing instance's mainComponent.id
const instance = variant.findOne(n => n.name === 'icon-wrapper-instance' && n.type === 'INSTANCE');
const mainComponent = await instance.getMainComponentAsync();
const localNodeId = mainComponent.id;       // e.g. '5657:6767' — USE THIS
const publishedKey = mainComponent.key;     // e.g. '09f...59' — NOT for local INSTANCE_SWAP
```

## 3. `figma.createAutoLayout()` ships with a hidden default white fill

`figma.createAutoLayout()` and `figma.createFrame()` initialize the new
node with `fills = [{ type: 'SOLID', color: { r: 1, g: 1, b: 1 } }]`
by default. For visual containers that intentionally render a surface
(card backgrounds, sheet bases), that's fine — bind the fill to a token.
For **structural containers** that exist purely to hold children (slots,
rows, anatomy wrappers, layout shells), this default white fill is
invisible on a white page and silently breaks any "no raw colors"
audit.

### Rule

Any auto-layout frame created with `figma.createAutoLayout()` /
`figma.createFrame()` that doesn't intentionally render a surface MUST
`node.fills = []` immediately after creation. Don't wait for the audit
to find it.

```js
// WRONG — leaves a hidden white fill
const slot = figma.createAutoLayout('HORIZONTAL', { name: 'leading-icon' });
slot.visible = false;
parent.appendChild(slot);
// slot.fills is now [{ type: 'SOLID', color: { r: 1, g: 1, b: 1 } }]

// CORRECT — structural container, clear the fill
const slot = figma.createAutoLayout('HORIZONTAL', { name: 'leading-icon' });
slot.fills = [];
slot.visible = false;
parent.appendChild(slot);
```

## 4. `resize()` forces FIXED on both axes — and ancestor sizes don't propagate within a single script

Two related ordering bugs:

### 4a. `resize(w, h)` overrides `primaryAxisSizingMode` and `counterAxisSizingMode`

Setting auto-layout sizing modes before calling `resize()` looks like
it works (the modes show as `'AUTO'` in subsequent reads), but the
resize forces the dimensions to FIXED. The node won't HUG or FILL until
you re-declare it.

```js
// LOOKS RIGHT, ISN'T
const frame = figma.createAutoLayout('VERTICAL');
frame.primaryAxisSizingMode = 'AUTO';   // hug vertically
frame.resize(320, 80);                  // forces FIXED on both axes
// children added later don't make the frame hug — it stays at 80px tall

// CORRECT — declare sizing AFTER resize, OR after children are appended
const frame = figma.createAutoLayout('VERTICAL');
frame.resize(320, 80);
for (const child of children) frame.appendChild(child);
frame.layoutSizingVertical = 'HUG';     // now reflows to actual content height
```

### 4b. Size changes don't propagate to ancestors within one `use_figma` call

A child mutation that should change a parent's hugged size doesn't
update `parent.height` synchronously inside the same script. If your
build needs the settled parent height for downstream layout
(e.g. arranging variants in a grid based on actual heights), do the
size mutation in one call and the dependent layout in a **subsequent**
call. Reading `parent.height` immediately after the mutation returns
the OLD value.

```js
// First use_figma call
for (const wrapper of wrapperSet.children) {
  wrapper.layoutSizingVertical = 'HUG';
}
// wrapper.height STILL reports the pre-HUG value here.

// Second use_figma call (next script)
// Now wrapper.height reflects the hugged content. Grid reflow can use it.
```

## 5. Auto-layout has FIVE bindable spacing properties, not two

Auto-layout frames in the Plugin API expose five independent spacing
properties, each individually bindable to a `uds-space` variable:

- `paddingTop`
- `paddingBottom`
- `paddingLeft`
- `paddingRight`
- `itemSpacing`

There is no `paddingHorizontal` / `paddingVertical` shorthand on the
Plugin API. CSS shorthand and Tailwind utility classes (`px-4 py-2`,
`padding: 8px 16px`) train the eye to think in horizontal/vertical
pairs; the Plugin API is per-side. A factory or sync script that
binds `paddingLeft` and `paddingRight` and forgets the vertical pair
ships a node where the top and bottom paddings are raw pixel literals
that escape every "is this bound to a token?" check.

The error mode is silent: visually the frame still renders correctly
in the default density mode, and the bound horizontal axes look fine
on inspection. The unbound vertical pair only surfaces when the design
system flips density (`[data-density="comfortable"]` re-resolves every
space token but leaves the raw `8` literals stranded) or when a code-gen
tool reports the resolved values per axis.

This is purely a question of **binding state across sides**, not value
symmetry across sides. A pill that legitimately wants `paddingLeft = 16`
and `paddingRight = 12` (different values per side because the leading
icon and trailing chevron need different breathing room) is fine — the
fix is "every side bound to its own appropriate space variable," not
"every side bound to the same space variable."

### Wrong → correct

```js
// WRONG — two of the five spacing properties bound, the rest stranded
const pill = figma.createAutoLayout('HORIZONTAL', { name: 'pill' });
pill.setBoundVariable('paddingLeft',  spaceVar200);
pill.setBoundVariable('paddingRight', spaceVar150);
pill.paddingTop = 8;       // raw literal — silently bypasses density
pill.paddingBottom = 8;    // raw literal — silently bypasses density
pill.itemSpacing = 12;     // raw literal — silently bypasses density

// CORRECT — every used spacing property bound to a uds-space variable
pill.setBoundVariable('paddingLeft',   spaceVar200);  // 16px
pill.setBoundVariable('paddingRight',  spaceVar150);  // 12px
pill.setBoundVariable('paddingTop',    spaceVar100);  //  8px
pill.setBoundVariable('paddingBottom', spaceVar100);  //  8px
pill.setBoundVariable('itemSpacing',   spaceVar150);  // 12px
```

### Helper signature contract

Any factory helper that wraps padding configuration MUST accept all
five properties (or accept a `{ top, right, bottom, left, gap }`
object). Two-axis helpers (`setPadding(node, h, v)`) are an
anti-pattern — they bind whichever pair the helper takes (the `h`
arguments to `paddingLeft` and `paddingRight`) and leave the other
pair as raw pixel literals. If the real component happens to want the
same value on both sides of a given axis, pass the same variable to
both sides; that's still five `setBoundVariable` calls. The
requirement is "every side bound," not "every side equal."

## 6. Effects must bind via `setEffectStyleIdAsync`, never `node.effects = [...]`

The same shape of problem as fills: `node.effects` accepts a literal
array of effect objects, and writing
`node.effects = [{ type: 'DROP_SHADOW', color: ..., offset: ..., radius: ..., spread: ... }]`
produces a visually-shadowed node that escapes every "is this bound to
a token?" check. The right path is
`await node.setEffectStyleIdAsync(style.id)` after
`await figma.importStyleByKeyAsync(EFFECT_STYLE_KEY)`.

The error mode is silent: the visual output is a shadow; an audit that
only checks `effects.length > 0` won't tell you whether `effectStyleId`
is set. And — like the padding asymmetry — the literal values in the
script may not even match the design system's depth values, but
nothing fails because the bytes that hit Figma are technically valid
effect data.

### Wrong → correct

```js
// WRONG — raw effects literal, even if numerically right
node.effects = [{
  type: 'DROP_SHADOW',
  color: { r: 0, g: 0, b: 0, a: 0.1 },
  offset: { x: 0, y: 2 },
  radius: 8,
  spread: 0,
  visible: true,
  blendMode: 'NORMAL'
}];
// node.effectStyleId is still '' — audit can't see this is "depth-100"

// CORRECT — bind to the design system's depth-100 effect style
const depth100 = await figma.importStyleByKeyAsync(DEPS.effectStyles.depth100);
await node.setEffectStyleIdAsync(depth100.id);
// node.effectStyleId now holds the style ID — audit passes, and a
// designer flipping the depth scale sees this node update with the rest.
```

### Audit signature

A factory or sync audit that wants to flag unbound effects MUST check
both:

- `node.effects.length > 0` (there's a visible effect at all), AND
- `node.effectStyleId === ''` (no effect style attached)

Either condition alone is insufficient. Nodes with no effects are
trivially "bound" in the vacuous sense; nodes with a style attached
but custom effect overrides on top should be flagged as a separate
"effect style overridden" finding.

## 7. UDS tokens, effect styles, and text styles are REMOTE — `getLocal*Async` returns empty

UDS Components subscribes the **UDS Tokens** library. Every color
variable, effect style (`uds/effect/elevation/depth-*`), and text
style (`uds/text/*`) lives in that remote library, NOT locally in the
UDS Components file. Consequence:

- `await figma.variables.getLocalVariablesAsync('COLOR')` → `[]`
- `await figma.getLocalEffectStylesAsync()` → `[]`
- `await figma.getLocalTextStylesAsync()` → `[]`

Reading empty from those does NOT mean the tokens/styles don't exist —
it means they're remote. Concluding "there's no elevation style, I'll
hardcode `node.effects = [...]`" is the trap (and it violates §6). The
factory hit exactly this: `getLocalEffectStylesAsync()` returned `0`,
but `uds/effect/elevation/depth-100..500` were in the library the whole
time.

### Discover + bind remote tokens/styles

1. **Discover** via `search_design_system` scoped to the UDS Tokens
   library key (`includeVariables` / `includeStyles: true`). Keyword
   the query well — an effect-style sweep needs `elevation` / `shadow`
   / `depth`; a color sweep needs the role word. The result carries the
   `key`.
2. **Import** into the file before binding. Mind the namespaces:
   - Variables: `const v = await figma.variables.importVariableByKeyAsync(KEY)`
     — note `figma.variables.`; bare `figma.importVariableByKeyAsync`
     does NOT exist and throws
     `no such property 'importVariableByKeyAsync'`.
   - Effect / text styles: `const s = await figma.importStyleByKeyAsync(KEY)`
     — this one IS on the `figma` root.
3. **Bind** the imported object: `node.setBoundVariable(prop, v)` /
   `figma.variables.setBoundVariableForPaint(paint, 'color', v)` /
   `await node.setEffectStyleIdAsync(s.id)` /
   `await textNode.setTextStyleIdAsync(s.id)`.

A token already used elsewhere in the file is already imported — reuse
its in-file `VariableID:…` via `getVariableByIdAsync` instead of
re-importing. Re-import by key only for tokens/styles the file isn't
using yet (e.g. binding a brand-new elevation style to a popover).

## 8. Variable-length copy must WRAP — `textAutoResize = 'WIDTH_AND_HEIGHT'` overflows on long content

A text node created/cloned with the default `textAutoResize =
'WIDTH_AND_HEIGHT'` grows horizontally to fit its content and never
wraps. For a fixed label that's fine. For any node that holds
**variable-length copy** — helper/error text, descriptions, option
supporting text, the value/input line — it means a long string blows
past the component's width instead of wrapping onto a second line. The
field still renders fine with the short default string, so it passes a
casual look and only breaks when real (long) copy lands.

### Rule

A copy-bearing text node inside a width-bound auto-layout component
MUST be set to wrap:

- `textNode.textAutoResize = 'HEIGHT'`  (fixed width, grows in height)
- `textNode.layoutSizingHorizontal = 'FILL'`  (take the row's width)
- and the node's row/parent must hug height
  (`layoutSizingVertical = 'HUG'`) so the wrapped second line shows
  instead of clipping.

The component needs a definite width for wrapping to have a bound — a
`FIXED`-width root (or a `FILL` chain up to one) gives the text a width
to wrap within. A fully width-HUGGING component has no wrap point, so
the auto-width text is the only thing setting the width; fixing wrap
there means giving the component a real width first.

### Wrong → correct

```js
// WRONG — helper text auto-grows in width, overflows on long copy
helper.textAutoResize = 'WIDTH_AND_HEIGHT';   // default — never wraps

// CORRECT — fixed width, wraps to height; row hugs the extra line
helper.textAutoResize = 'HEIGHT';
helper.layoutSizingHorizontal = 'FILL';
helperRow.layoutSizingVertical = 'HUG';
```

This bit the Combobox helper text — the same root cause as a missing
editable value property: text nodes built for the short demo string,
not for real content.

### Responsive wrap needs a `minWidth` guard

A `FILL`/`layoutGrow=1` text node that wraps (`textAutoResize='HEIGHT'`)
will collapse to **per-character** wrapping ("L / a / b / e / l") when
its container gets narrow — e.g. when it shares a row with a trailing
affordance (a required dot, a counter) that eats the width. Set a
`minWidth` on the text node (e.g. `textNode.minWidth = 40`) so it wraps
word-by-word and never degrades to one glyph per line. This is what
makes a wrapping label/field actually responsive.

### Do NOT collapse a variant axis that encodes incompatible modes

The cloned `udc-label` had a `Multiline` axis (False=hug, True=wrap).
"Simplifying" by collapsing it into a single always-wrap mode broke the
component: a `FILL` wrapping label cannot also sit inline with a
trailing required dot / "(optional)" without collapsing or leaving an
ugly gap — hug and wrap are genuinely different modes, which is exactly
why the axis existed. Before collapsing any axis, check whether its
values represent mutually-incompatible layouts; if they do, keep the
axis. And when a cloned/inherited structure keeps fighting an
edit (nested-instance sizing that won't reset cleanly), stop patching
it and rebuild the component from scratch — that's faster and cleaner
than wrestling the clone.

## 9. Bound-variable paints can still render their literal fallback — bake the resolved value

`figma.variables.setBoundVariableForPaint({ type:'SOLID', color:{r:0,g:0,b:0} }, 'color', v)`
returns a paint that *binds* the variable but keeps whatever literal
`color` you passed (here black) as the design-time fallback. Two
situations make that literal show up on canvas instead of the resolved
token value:

- **Component / variant ROOT fills** render the literal fallback, not
  the live-resolved variable, in screenshots and on canvas. (Child
  frames resolve live; the component node itself shows the baked
  literal.)
- **Re-binding a variable a node already had** — e.g. you `clone()` a
  component whose root is bound to `surface-main`, then re-assign
  `fills=[bind(surfaceMain)]` — keeps the literal you passed (black)
  rather than re-baking the resolved value. Binding a *different*
  variable bakes the resolved literal correctly, which is why the bug
  looks selective: only the same-variable rebinds go black.

Net effect from the factory: every Default/Focus variant root (rebound
to the same `surface-main` the base already had) rendered solid black,
while Hover/Selected (different vars) were fine.

### Rule

Bake the resolved value into the literal `color` AND keep the binding:

```js
// WRONG — literal stays black; variant root renders black
node.fills = [figma.variables.setBoundVariableForPaint(
  { type:'SOLID', color:{ r:0, g:0, b:0 } }, 'color', v)];

// CORRECT — resolve for this node, bake the literal, keep the binding
const rgb = v.resolveForConsumer(node).value;   // { r, g, b, a }
node.fills = [{
  type: 'SOLID',
  color: { r: rgb.r, g: rgb.g, b: rgb.b },
  boundVariables: { color: { type: 'VARIABLE_ALIAS', id: v.id } }
}];
```

A whole-set fix is a post-pass that walks every node's `fills` /
`strokes`, and for each paint with `boundVariables.color`, rebuilds it
with the resolved literal. Cheap and idempotent.

## 10. Component `description` HTML-escapes `<`/`>` — use `descriptionMarkdown`

Setting `componentSet.description = '<<UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT v1>> …'`
stores `&lt;&lt;UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT v1&gt;&gt;` — the `description`
setter HTML-escapes angle brackets. Any reader matching the literal
`<<UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT v1>>` delimiter (the
[`figma-component-inspector`](../agents/figma-component-inspector.md)
contract-block parser) then misses the block, and the round-trip into
`spec.json` lands empty.

`descriptionMarkdown` stores the literal text (`<<` survives). Write the
factory-contract block via `node.descriptionMarkdown`, and verify:

```js
node.descriptionMarkdown = block;
if (node.descriptionMarkdown.indexOf('<<UDS-FACTORY-CONTRACT v1>>') < 0)
  throw 'contract delimiter was escaped/lost';
```

`description` is the escaped HTML render of the markdown; treat
`descriptionMarkdown` as the source of truth.

## 11. `setEffectStyleIdAsync('')` leaves a stale effect literal — clear with `effects = []`

Detaching an effect style does not remove the effect. After
`await node.setEffectStyleIdAsync('')`, `node.effects` still holds the
previous style's shadow as a raw literal, so the node both renders a
shadow you meant to drop AND fails the "raw effects literal, no effect
style" gate (§6).

```js
// WRONG — detaches the style but keeps a stale raw drop-shadow
await node.setEffectStyleIdAsync('');

// CORRECT — to make a node intentionally flat (no elevation)
node.effects = [];
```

Use `setEffectStyleIdAsync(otherStyle.id)` to *change* elevation; use
`effects = []` to *remove* it.

## 12. Nesting a DS component is not enough — expose it (`isExposedInstance`) to surface its properties

A nested instance's own component properties (e.g. `udc-icon-wrapper`'s
`Icon` glyph-swap and `Size`) do NOT appear on the parent component's
instance panel by default. Adding a top-level `INSTANCE_SWAP` property
on the parent swaps the *whole wrapper* for another component — it does
not let the designer change the glyph inside the wrapper, which is
almost always what they actually want. (Factory miss: the Metric Card
`trendIcon` swap replaced the wrapper but exposed no way to pick the
glyph.)

To surface the nested wrapper's own controls, set
`isExposedInstance = true` on the nested instance (writable on primary
instances inside a `ComponentNode` / `ComponentSetNode`; set it on the
instance in *every* variant):

```js
const icon = variant.findOne(n => n.name === 'icon' && n.type === 'INSTANCE');
icon.isExposedInstance = true;   // surfaces the wrapper's Icon + Size on the parent
```

Verify by instantiating the set and reading `instance.exposedInstances`
→ each should list the wrapper's `componentProperties` (`Icon#…`,
`Size`). Prefer exposing the nested glyph/size controls over a
whole-wrapper `INSTANCE_SWAP` when the intent is "swap the glyph"; keep
both only if replacing the entire wrapper is a real use case.

Component-specific corollary: `udc-icon-wrapper`'s rendered glyph color
lives on the `Union` `BOOLEAN_OPERATION` child (a bound paint), not the
deepest `VECTOR`. To tint a wrapper per tone, rebind that node's fill.

## 13. Setting an icon-wrapper `Icon` swap to a library glyph: import once, swap by NODE ID

To put a library icon (a Material Symbols glyph, etc.) into a nested
`udc-icon-wrapper`'s `Icon` INSTANCE_SWAP property, the glyph must first
exist **in-file**, and the swap value is that in-file component's
**node ID** — not the published key:

```js
// 1. Import the icon set ONCE — capture the returned set; reuse it.
const mv = await figma.importComponentSetByKeyAsync(MORE_VERT_SET_KEY);
const outlined = mv.children.find(c => /Outlined/.test(c.name)); // a COMPONENT
// 2. Set the wrapper's Icon property to the imported variant's NODE ID.
const key = Object.keys(iconWrapper.componentProperties).find(k => /^Icon/.test(k));
iconWrapper.setProperties({ [key]: outlined.id });   // e.g. '8836:4' — CORRECT
```

Two error signatures, both from `setProperties` on the icon swap:

| Passed value | Error | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Published component **key** (`'9abc28…'`) | `Property value is incompatible with component property type` | §2 mis-scope. This property's existing default is an in-file node id, so its targets are LOCAL — it wants a node id, not a remote key. |
| A **node id that doesn't exist** (stale, or from a rolled-back atomic call) | `Value for instance swap component property is invalid` | The id format is accepted but resolves to no valid swap target. A prior `use_figma` that errored rolled back its import, so the id it returned is dead. |

`importComponentSetByKeyAsync` is **not idempotent** — every call mints
a fresh in-file copy (you'll get `8832:2`, then `8836:2`, …). Import
once, capture the set id, reuse it across the whole run; don't
re-import per variant or you litter the file with duplicate icon sets.
Those duplicates are **null-parented** — the imported set's `.parent` is
`null` and it sits on no page — UNLIKE `clone()` / `createInstance()`,
which land on `currentPage` (§16). So you can't find or sweep them by
walking a page's children: an unreferenced re-import is an invisible
orphan, and a referenced one is reachable only via an instance's
`mainComponent.parent`. Prevention (import once) is the only clean fix —
there's no after-the-fact page sweep. (Verified on the nav-header
2026-06-16 cleanup: re-imports across calls left exactly the two
referenced chevron sets reachable via their instances and zero litter on
the draft page.)
The icon-wrapper's `Icon` `preferredValues` is a soft UI hint (it
points at one example set), not a hard restriction — any in-file glyph
component works as the value.

### Swapping a nested instance to a different component SET preserves the node but reapply its property references

To change a nested instance's emphasis (e.g. `udc-button-primary` →
`udc-button-ghost`), use `instance.swapComponent(targetVariant)` with a
specific variant COMPONENT (not the set). The instance node id is
preserved, but defensively capture and reapply its
`componentPropertyReferences` after the swap so a parent-driven binding
(e.g. `visible: showMenu`) survives:

```js
const refs = Object.assign({}, menu.componentPropertyReferences);
menu.swapComponent(ghostIconOnlyVariant);   // a COMPONENT, e.g. '5140:846'
menu.componentPropertyReferences = refs;     // re-pin visible:showMenu etc.
menu.isExposedInstance = true;               // re-expose if it was exposed
```

This was the Metric Card overflow-menu fix (primary → ghost icon-only
with a `more_vert` glyph).

### A nested set with authoring errors blocks `setProperties` — swap if you can, flag if you can't

If a nested component SET carries internal authoring errors, *every*
property-layer API against it throws — not just the read. Both of these
fail:

- `nestedSet.componentPropertyDefinitions` → `in get_componentPropertyDefinitions: Component set has existing errors`
- `nestedInstance.setProperties({ ... })` on an instance of that set → same class of failure

`udc-badge` (`5794:7948`) is the known UDS case: the error originates on
the badge set, and **anything that nests a badge inherits the failure**
(an accordion row's status pill, a nav "My Work" count pill, etc.). It is
NOT a bug in the host component — see
`.cursor/figma/state/last-sync.json` for the prior attribution.

The fallback is `instance.swapComponent(targetVariant)` (§13 above): it
bypasses the property layer and writes the swap directly, so a straight
variant change still works — e.g. swapping the badge to its subtle
(non-prominent) variant.

But `swapComponent` is a **partial** fallback, not a cure. When you can't
resolve the exact target variant safely — e.g. flipping the badge's tone
to neutral on a Disabled row, where the errored set makes reliable
variant lookup untrustworthy — do NOT force it. Flag it as a Phase C
finding and let the designer fix the source set. The accordion-item
Disabled variants shipped with the green Success badge for exactly this
reason: swap-to-subtle succeeded, tone-to-neutral was flagged rather than
forced.

```js
// WRONG — the badge set has authoring errors; this throws.
badgeInstance.setProperties({ 'Prominent': 'False', 'Variant': 'Neutral' });

// PARTIAL FALLBACK — a direct swap to a known-good variant works…
badgeInstance.swapComponent(subtleSuccessVariant);   // OK: subtle style applied

// …but when the right target can't be pinned down safely, don't guess —
// leave the visual as-is and report it in the Phase C gate.
```

## 14. A host-component audit must attribute each node to its owning instance — `skipInvisibleInstanceChildren` is not enough

When you audit a component's OWN anatomy — looking for stray/cruft
nodes, focus rings, layer-hygiene violations, or exposure coverage — a
node returned by `host.findAll(...)` may belong to a **nested DS
instance**, not the host. Flagging it as the host's is a false positive.

`figma.skipInvisibleInstanceChildren = true` is NOT a reliable filter
for this. It did not keep a hidden `focus outline` frame *inside* a
nested `udc-button-ghost` instance out of `findAll` on the host
component set. Filtering only `n.type !== 'INSTANCE'` is also
insufficient — the offending node was a plain `FRAME`; it was its
*ancestor* that was the instance.

### Rule

Before treating a node as the host's own, walk its parent chain and
skip it if ANY ancestor is an `INSTANCE`:

```js
function ownedByNestedInstance(node, hostRoot) {
  let p = node.parent;
  while (p && p !== hostRoot) {
    if (p.type === 'INSTANCE') return true;   // belongs to a nested DS component
    p = p.parent;
  }
  return false;
}
// host-own audit:
const ownNodes = host.findAll(n => !ownedByNestedInstance(n, host));
```

Failure mode: the Metric Card stamp-only upgrade audit flagged the
overflow button's OWN hidden focus ring (`focus outline`, 44×56, parent
`button`, owned by `udc-button-ghost`) as host cruft and tried to
delete it — `n.remove()` threw `Removing this node is not allowed`
(instance-owned), atomic rollback, no change. The tell that it was
button-owned, not host cruft: it was present only in variants that
carried the nested `menu` button and absent from the `Add` variant
(which has no menu). An ancestor-instance check would have excluded it
up front.

## 15. Detect state elements structurally, not by name substring — Material glyph names collide

Searching for a focus ring (or any state element) by name with a
substring like `/focus|ring|outline/i` collides with Material Symbols
glyph instance names: `people_outline`, `add_circle_outline` both
contain `outline`; other passes collide with `more_vert`,
`trending_up` / `trending_down`, etc. `findOne` then returns a GLYPH
instead of the ring and the audit silently inspects the wrong node.

### Rule

Detect a focus ring by its STRUCTURE, not its name:

```js
function isFocusRing(n) {
  return n.type === 'FRAME'
    && n.layoutPositioning === 'ABSOLUTE'
    && Array.isArray(n.fills) && n.fills.length === 0
    && Array.isArray(n.strokes) && n.strokes[0]
    && n.strokes[0].boundVariables
    && n.strokes[0].boundVariables.color;   // bound to outline-focus-visible
}
```

Naming corollary: keep ring layer names distinct and consistent
(`focus-outline`, hyphenated) and never rely on the name for detection.
The Metric Card draft carries two similarly-named rings — the card's own
`focus-outline` (hyphen, card-sized, on Focus variants) and the nested
button's `focus outline` (space, 44×56) — which is exactly why a
substring match is unsafe.

## 16. `currentPage` resets every call — `clone()` / `createInstance()` parent there, so multi-call builds leak onto a live page

`figma.currentPage` is reset at the start of **every** `use_figma` call to
whatever page is open in the editor. It is NOT the value you set with
`setCurrentPageAsync` in a previous call, and NOT reliably "the first
page" (the
[`figma-component-card` gotchas](../skills/figma-component-card/references/gotchas.md)
say "first page" — the factory observed it land on whatever page the
editor had active, a *live* page). Never assume the page persists across
calls.

This matters because `node.clone()` and `component.createInstance()`
parent the new node to `currentPage` unless you immediately `appendChild`
it somewhere else. So in a fresh call, cloning a base that lives on your
draft page drops the clones onto the editor's active page — often the live
library page.

### Symptoms

- A later `figma.combineAsVariants(nodes, parent)` throws
  `in combineAsVariants: Grouped nodes must be in the same page as the parent`
  — the clones and the intended parent are on different pages.
- Stray clones (plus any side-effect nodes from a call that threw and
  rolled back partway) sit on the **live** page as orphans. This is a real
  write outside the draft sandbox, not a cosmetic glitch.

### Rule

1. Do the **clone → reparent → combine** sequence inside a SINGLE
   `use_figma` call, so the page context can't reset mid-flow.
2. `await figma.setCurrentPageAsync(draftPage)` at the TOP of that call.
3. Explicitly `draftPage.appendChild(node)` (or append to a frame on the
   draft page) for every created/cloned node — do not trust `currentPage`
   to keep them in the right place.
4. After any multi-call build that errored partway, sweep the live page's
   direct children for nodes tagged with your `run_id` and remove the
   orphans. Cleanup is mandatory here, not optional.

### Wrong → correct

```js
// WRONG — fresh call: currentPage is whatever's open (often a LIVE page).
// clone() parents to currentPage, so the clones land off the draft page.
const base = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('9254:1');   // base variant on the draft page
const clones = [];
for (let i = 0; i < 9; i++) clones.push(base.clone()); // each clone → currentPage (live page!)
figma.combineAsVariants([base, ...clones], draftPage);
// Throws: Grouped nodes must be in the same page as the parent
// …and leaves 9 orphan clones on the live page.

// CORRECT — one call: pin the page, appendChild every node onto the draft, then combine
const draft = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync(DRAFT_PAGE_ID);
await figma.setCurrentPageAsync(draft);
const base = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('9254:1');
const all = [base];
for (let i = 0; i < 9; i++) {
  const c = base.clone();
  draft.appendChild(c);                                // explicit — never rely on currentPage
  c.setSharedPluginData('dsb', 'run_id', RUN_ID);
  all.push(c);
}
const set = figma.combineAsVariants(all, draft);
```

### Orphan sweep (run after a build that threw partway)

```js
const live = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync(LIVE_PAGE_ID);
await live.loadAsync();
for (const n of live.children) {
  if (n.getSharedPluginData('dsb', 'run_id') === RUN_ID) n.remove();
}
```

This bit the accordion-item build: nine cloned variants and an empty
`_glyph-sources` frame + an orphan icon instance leaked onto the live
`UDS Version: 0.3` page across separate calls, `combineAsVariants` failed
on the page mismatch, and the strays had to be swept before Phase C could
pass its leak check.

## 17. An empty auto-layout frame keeps its 100px creation default — a HUG axis can't shrink with no children

When you use an empty frame as a flex spacer (the "push the last item to
the right" trick in a horizontal toolbar / row), `figma.createFrame()`
ships it at the default 100×100. Setting `layoutSizingHorizontal = 'FILL'`
makes it grow along the main axis correctly — but if the CROSS axis is left
at `HUG`, the frame has no children to hug down to, so it RETAINS the 100px
default on that axis. In a parent whose counter-axis sizing is `HUG` /
`AUTO` (especially with `counterAxisAlignItems = 'CENTER'`), the parent then
sizes to the 100px spacer instead of the real content — a 36px button row
silently becomes a 112px-tall strip.

### Wrong → correct

```js
// WRONG — spacer grows horizontally but stays 100px tall, inflating the row
const spacer = figma.createFrame();
toolbar.appendChild(spacer);
spacer.layoutSizingHorizontal = 'FILL';   // main axis: correct (grows)
// cross axis left at HUG → empty frame keeps its 100px default → row hugs to 112px

// CORRECT — fill the cross axis too so the spacer tracks real content height
spacer.layoutSizingHorizontal = 'FILL';
spacer.layoutSizingVertical   = 'FILL';    // now matches the 36px button row
```

### Rule

A flex-spacer frame must be `FILL` on BOTH axes — main axis to grow, cross
axis to track content — never left `HUG` on the cross axis. After building
any auto-layout container, assert its measured cross-axis size ≈
(tallest/widest real child + padding); a container ~100px larger than its
largest real child is the empty-HUG-spacer smell. The Phase C
layer-hygiene/spacing gates won't catch this — it's a sizing bug, not a
binding bug — so the measured-size check is the tripwire.

This bit the rich-text-editor 2026-06-11 build: a 112px toolbar (should
have been 48px) because `toolbar-spacer` was `FILL` horizontal but `HUG`
vertical, holding the 100px default; the centered toolbar sized to the
spacer, not the buttons.

## 18. Visibility doesn't behave naively across the variant / instance / property boundary

A node's `visible` interacts with component properties and instance
overrides in two non-obvious ways. Both bit the nav-header 2026-06-16
edit. They are the same underlying truth — `visible` is not a plain
per-node boolean once a component property or an instance override is in
play — seen from two directions.

### 18a. Setting a variant's `.visible` mutates the bound property's default for the WHOLE set

When a node's visibility is bound to a BOOLEAN component property (e.g.
`Show Trailing`), the node's `visible` is no longer an independent
per-variant value — it IS the property's default. Setting
`variant.findOne(...).visible = true` inside one variant therefore
flips the property default and turns the node on across **every**
variant in the set, not just the one you touched.

The error mode is silent: the script "succeeds," the variant you edited
looks right, and the regression shows up on all the OTHER variants
(every nav row sprouted a trailing chevron after one parent variant's
trailing slot was set visible).

```js
// WRONG — trailing slot's visibility is bound to the `Show Trailing`
// component property. This sets the PROPERTY DEFAULT, not this variant.
const parent = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('8360:89');
parent.findOne(n => n.name === 'trailing-slot').visible = true;
// → every variant in the set now shows its trailing slot.
```

The fix depends on what you actually want:

- **Per-variant visibility that should follow a variant axis** (e.g.
  only `Kind=Parent*` shows a chevron): the node should NOT be bound to
  a shared toggle at all. Delete the component property, then set
  `.visible` per variant — now each variant owns its own value.

  ```js
  const set = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('8360:208');
  set.deleteComponentProperty('Show Trailing#8360:60'); // unbind the shared toggle
  for (const v of set.children) {
    const t = v.findOne(n => n.name === 'trailing-slot');
    if (t) t.visible = v.name.includes('Parent'); // per-variant, independent now
  }
  ```

- **A consumer-facing toggle you want to keep**: change the property's
  default with the property API, not by poking a node, and set the
  default to the conservative value (usually `false`), then override
  per *instance* (§18b), not per variant.

  ```js
  set.editComponentProperty('Show Trailing#8360:60', { defaultValue: false });
  ```

### 18b. Pre-existing instances carry their own `.visible` overrides that MASK a variant change

The mirror image: after you fix a variant so a node SHOULD show, existing
instances created earlier can still hide it, because an instance stores
its own visibility override that wins over the main component. The
variant looks fixed in the set but the assembled composition (the
nav-list instance) still hides the chevron.

```js
// The set's parent variants now show the chevron, but this instance
// was created earlier with a visible:false override on that node —
// it still renders hidden.
const navList = await figma.getNodeByIdAsync('8364:141');
for (const row of navList.children) {
  if (row.type !== 'INSTANCE') continue;
  // re-assert the intended value per instance, OR reset overrides
  const t = row.findOne(n => n.name === 'trailing-slot');
  if (t) t.visible = /* the value this row should have */;
}
```

Reset the instance override (or re-assert the intended value per
instance), or recreate the instances from the fixed main. Don't assume a
variant-level fix propagates to instances that predate it — overrides
persist.

### 18c. Delete the orphaned component property when you remove the node it drove

Removing the node a component property pointed at (e.g. deleting a
`caret-gutter` whose chevron was the `chevronSlot` INSTANCE_SWAP target)
leaves a defunct property on the set. It clutters the instance panel and
can throw on later property-layer calls. Sweep it:

```js
set.deleteComponentProperty('chevronSlot#8360:24'); // node it referenced is gone
```

